<h2>Events in August 2018</h2>
<br><br>
There was a long drought period in Western and Central Europe, but in Southern Europe more precipitation than usual was reported. In mid August the blocking high pressure area ceased to exist and a more western circulation was established. At the end of August a depression, a so-called Genoa Low (Figure 1) developed just off the Ligurian coast, which caused severe weather in Northern Italy and Slovenia. At several places in Piemonte and Lombardia there was torrential rain causing severe flooding. This extreme event contributed to the higher precipitation sums as depicted in Figure 11. Further, due to the strong convective conditions thunderstorms developed and even tornadoes were reported.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/aug2018/Analyse_2018083100_png.png"><img alt="" src="../images/aug2018/Analyse_2018083100_png.png" width="250px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 1 Genoa Low on the analysed weather map at 31 August 2018 00 UTC (Source: KNMI)</em>
<br><br>
<h2>Specific climate indicators for August 2018</h2>
<br><br>
In most of Europe the number of cold days was lower than in the reference period 1981-2010 (Figure 2). As ‘cold’ relates to the lowest 10 percentile range, the reference number of cold days is about 3. In Norway and Sweden the number of cold nights was relatively high.
<br><br>
