<br><br>
<br><br>
The number of summer days, with a maximum temperature of 25&#176;or more, shows a strong south-north gradient (Figure 4). In Southwest and Southeast Europe (almost) all days were summer days. In Ireland, most of UK and Norway (almost) no summer days occurred.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/aug2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_su_2018_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_SU_baselayers_overlay_2018-08-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/aug2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_su_2018_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_SU_baselayers_overlay_2018-08-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<a href="../images/aug2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_su_2018_month_nc__2018-08-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/aug2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_su_2018_month_nc__2018-08-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 4: Summer days in August 2018 (Based on E-OBS)</em>
<br><br>
<br><br>
In Southwest and Southeast Europe there were more than 20 consecutive dry days (Figure 5). A dry day is defined as a day with a total precipitation of less than 1 mm. Although there is generally a positive correlation between the number of summer days and number of consecutive dry days, in Central Europe the number of summer days was large but the number of consecutive dry days was small. Nevertheless, rain events were very localized and rain amounts were not sufficient to compensate the widespread soil deficits in Central Europe.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/aug2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_cdd_2018_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_CDD_baselayers_overlay_2018-08-16T00-00-00Z_large.png" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/aug2018/Stateofclimate_Indices_cdd_2018_month_nc_baselayers_world_polygons_CDD_baselayers_overlay_2018-08-16T00-00-00Z.png" ></a>
